00:06:05.241 --> 00:06:06.397
to evaluate these integrals,

00:06:06.397 --> 00:06:07.629
you'll see that one of
the most powerful ideas

00:06:07.629 --> 00:06:09.563
is being able to decompose
them in this way.

00:06:09.563 --> 00:06:14.297
To say, okay, if I'm taking
the definite integral from

00:06:14.297 --> 00:06:19.297
zero to one of x squared, plus sine of x,

00:06:19.814 --> 00:06:21.563
which you may or may not
have learned to do so far,

00:06:21.563 --> 00:06:23.362
you can at least start to break this down.

00:06:23.362 --> 00:06:25.030
You can say okay, well this
is going to be the same

00:06:25.030 --> 00:06:29.796
thing as the integral from
zero to one of x squared, dx,

00:06:29.796 --> 00:06:34.796
plus the integral from zero
to one of sine of x, dx.

00:06:35.847 --> 00:06:37.180
And you see this is one
of the most powerful

00:06:37.180 --> 00:06:40.837
principles of definite
integrals, to make them,

00:06:40.837 --> 00:06:42.162
when you start to try to compute them,

00:06:42.162 --> 00:06:45.536
or even sometimes conceptualize
what they're representing.

